===Etymology 2===
{{ja-kanjitab|わたくし|yomi=k}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=わたくし|私|tr=watakusi}}.

A surface analysis suggests a [[Appendix:Glossary#compound|compound]] term. However, no likely [[etyma]] are known.
* From first-person pronoun {{m|ja|我|tr=wa||[[I]], [[me]]}} + ''takusi'': although the first element seems likely, the original meaning of ''watakushi'' was “{{m|en|private}}”, as opposed to “{{m|en|public}}”, with no first-person pronoun usage until the late 13th century.
* From {{ja-r|我|わ|t=[[I]], [[me]]}} + {{ja-r|つ|t=genitive marker}}, and the other parts remain unknown.
* From ''wata'' + ''kusi'': the only phonetic matches are {{m|ja|綿|tr=wata||[[cotton]]; cotton [[batting]]}}, {{m|ja|腸|tr=wata||[[gut]]s, one's [[innard]]s|pos=likely derived from the “batting” sense}}, {{m|ja|海|tr=wata||[[sea]], [[ocean]]}} + {{m|ja|串|tr=kusi||[[skewer]]}}, {{m|ja|奇し|tr=kusi||[[magic#Adjective|magic]], [[fantastic]], [[supernatural#Adjective|supernatural]]|pos=adjective}}, {{m|ja|酒|tr=kusi||[[alcoholic]] [[beverage]]|pos=likely derived from the “magic” sense}}, {{m|ja|櫛|tr=kusi||[[comb]]}}.
* The first element may come from {{ja-r|内|うち|one's own, my, our}}, and the second element remains unknown.

The meaning evolved over time from “{{m|en|private}}” or “{{m|en|privatization}}”, to refer to things that are {{m|en|personal}}, to refer to one's own {{m|en|person}}, and then finally to serve as a generic first-person pronoun. The full form ''watakushi'' is still used in modern Japanese as a formal, highly [[polite]] first-person pronoun. The abbreviated form ''watashi'' is now the most common and neutrally [[polite]] first-person pronoun.

